==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*duga-/*dox-'', from Indo-European ''*dheughe-'' ‘be ready, suffice’.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[duga]]/''daech'', Old Saxon ''dugan''/''dōg'' (Dutch [[deugen]]), Old High German [[tugan]]/''touc'' (German [[taugen]]), Old Norse [[duga]] (weak) (Swedish [[duga]]).  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[τευξομαι]], Russian [[дужий]].

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/'du:ɣan/}}

===Verb===
{{Unicode|'''dūgan'''}} (preterite-present: {{Unicode|'''dēag'''}} ‘it is useful’, '''dugon''' ‘they are useful’, '''dohte''' ‘it was useful’)
# to [[avail]], to be of use, to [[serve]]; to be [[fit]] or [[strong]]
#:''Ðonne his ellea deah'': when his valour avails.

